Then $\angle ADB = 180^\circ - 3\alpha$ and $\angle ADC = 180^\circ - 3\alpha,$ so $\angle BDA = \angle CDA = \alpha.$  Then by the Law of Sines on triangles $ABD$ and $ACD,$
\[\frac{BD}{\sin \alpha} = \frac{AD}{\sin \angle ABD} = \frac{11}{\sin 3 \alpha}\]and
\[\frac{CD}{\sin \alpha} = \frac{AD}{\sin \angle ACD} = \frac{11}{\sin 3 \alpha}.\]Hence, $BD = CD.$

Then $\angle BCD = 180^\circ - 2x.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BCD,$
\[100 = BC^2 = 2x^2 - 2x^2 \cos (180^\circ - 2x) = 2x^2 + 2x^2 \cos 2x = 2x^2 + 2x^2 (2 \cos^2 x - 1).\]Then $2x^2 \cos^2 x = 50,$ so $x^2 \cos^2 x = 25.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[BC^2 = 2x^2 - 2x^2 \cos 2x = 2x^2 - 2x^2 (2 \cos^2 x - 1) = 4x^2 \cos^2 x = 100.\]Then $BC = 10.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[AC^2 = AB^2 = 11^2 = 121.\]Then $AB = AC = 11.$  Then $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, so $\angle ABC = \angle ACB.$  Then
\[\angle BAC + 2 \angle ABC = 180^\circ,\]so $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = 60^\circ.$  Then $\triangle ABC$ is equilateral, so $AB = BC = AC = 11.$

